\description{
Generate a clinical trial randomization package.
}
\details{
Sample size can be supplied in one of two ways. Provide \code{n_per_group}
as a named vector for exact group counts, or provide \code{n_total} together
with \code{allocation_ratio}. If \code{allocation_ratio} is omitted, equal weights are
used. For \code{method = "simple"}, supplying \code{n_per_group} uses those exact
counts; if \code{n_per_group} is \code{NULL}, per-group counts are derived from
\code{n_total} and \code{allocation_ratio}. For \code{"block"} and \code{"stratified*"}, the
counts are otherwise driven by \code{n_total}/\code{allocation_ratio}, while
supplying \code{n_per_group} sets the effective total sample size via
\code{sum(n_per_group)}.

Stratified methods require \code{strata}, which must be a named list with at
most 6 factors. \code{stratum_n}, when supplied, must be named by the generated
\code{stratum_id} values or provided as a data frame with \code{stratum_id} and \code{n}.
For \code{"stratified_block"}, the requested stratum totals may be adjusted so
they are compatible with the available block sizes.

\code{center_var} must name one of the stratification factors. When supplied,
it can be used for center-specific random numbers, balance summaries, and
envelope generation. \code{random_no_by_center} only has an effect when
\code{center_var} is supplied.

The function always writes \code{blinded_site_table.csv},
\code{unblinded_master_table.csv}, \code{hashes_sha256.txt}, and \code{audit_log.jsonl} to
\code{output_dir}. \code{audit_log.jsonl} is written on every call, but it is not
currently stored in the \code{files} component. \code{generate_report},
\code{generate_random_envelope}, \code{generate_emergency_envelope}, and
\code{generate_reproducibility} control the optional Excel, PDF, and bundle
outputs.

\code{block_sizes} and \code{block_size_probs} are used by \code{"block"} and
\code{"stratified_block"}; the current \code{"stratified"} path does not use them.
\code{language} is currently accepted but unused by \code{rp_randomize()}. When the
reproducibility bundle is generated, \code{standalone_reproducibility_code = TRUE}
writes a standalone \code{reproduce_randomization.R} script that embeds the
package function definitions, while \code{FALSE} keeps a package-based script.
\code{encrypt_sensitive_outputs} currently performs only its password check and
does not itself encrypt outputs.
}
